This is an optional clause that allows an external authority to manage the definition of an entity.   Please see }{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "_Referencing_objects_by" }{{\*\datafield 
08d0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b0200000008000000180000005f005200650066006500720065006e00630069006e0067005f006f0062006a0065006300740073005f0062007900000000}}}{\fldrslt {\cs26\ul\cf2 Referencing objects by ID versus Value}}}{ for more details.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925567}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.2\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {AXIS{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925567}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
The name of the axis is for human consumption. The enumerated value that follows is to allow software to correctly overlay different coordinate systems.
\par 
\par If the optional AXIS terms are not present, then the default values are assumed.  They are
\par Geographic Coordinate Systems: }{\f2 AXIS[\'93Lon\'94,EAST],AXIS[\'93Lat\'94,NORTH]}{
\par Projected Coordinate System: }{\f2 AXIS[\'93X\'94,EAST],AXIS[\'93Y\'94,NORTH]}{
\par Geocentric Coordinate System: }{\f2 AXIS[\'93X\'94,OTHER],AXIS[\'93Y\'94,EAST],AXIS[\'93Z\'94,NORTH]}{
\par 
\par However, if these terms are present, and have non-default values, then implementations must be prepared to swap and reverse the coordinates of geometry before attempting to overlay graphics.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925568}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.3\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {COMPD_CS{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925568}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {This indicates a compou
nd coordinate system, which combines the coordinate of two other coordinate systems.  For example, a compound 3D coordinate system could be made up of a horizontal coordinate system and a vertical coordinate system.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925569}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.4\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {CONCAT_MT{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925569}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
A transform defined by the concatenation of sub-transforms.  The dimension of the output space of the first transform must match the dimension of the input space in the second transform (if defined), and so on for the remaining sub-transforms.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925570}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.5\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {DATUM{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925570} 
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
This indicates the horizontal datum, which corresponds to the procedure used to measure positions on the surface of the Earth. 
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925571}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.6\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {FITTED_CS{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925571}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {This indicates a fitted coordinate system.
\par 
\par The math transform is used to construct a map from the fitted coordinate system to the base coordinate system.  The transform is often an affine map.
\par  
\par The math transform works from the fitted CS to the base CS so that the fitted CS can have a smaller dimension that
 the base CS.  This is often quite useful.  For example, a fitted coordinate system could be a 2D plane approximately tangential to the Earth, but based on a WGS84 geocentric 3D coordinate system.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925572}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.7\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {GEOCCS{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925572}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {A 3D coordinate sys
tem, with its origin at the center of the Earth. The X axis points towards the prime meridian. The Y axis points East or West. The Z axis points North or South. By default the Z axis will point North, and the Y axis will point East (e.g. a right handed sy
stem), but you should check the axes for non-default values
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925573}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.8\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {GEOGCS{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925573} 
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
A coordinate system based on latitude and longitude. Some geographic coordinate systems are Lat/Lon, and some are Lon/Lat. You can find out which this is by
 examining the axes. You should also check the angular units, since not all geographic coordinate systems use degrees. 
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925574}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.9\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {INVERSE_MT{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925574}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {A math transform defined as the inverse of another transform.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925575}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.10\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {LOCAL_CS{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925575}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
This indicates a local, ungeoreferenced coordinate system.  Such coordinate systems are often used in CAD systems.  They can also be used for local surveys, where the relationship between the surveyed site and the rest of the world is not important.

\par 
\par The number of AXIS clauses indicates the dimension of the local coordinate system.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925576}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.11\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {PARAMETER{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925576}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {A named projection parameter value.
\par 
\par The units of the parameter must be inferred from its context.  If the parameter is 
inside a PROJCS, then its units will match the units of the PROJCS.  If the parameter is inside a PARAM_MT, then its units will be meters and degrees for linear and angular values respectively.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925577}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.12\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {PARAM_MT{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925577}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {A parameterized math transform.
\par 
\par All the linear parameters are expressed in meters, and all the angular parameters are expressed in degrees. Other parameters should use S.I. units where possible.  (E.g. use Kg for mass, and seconds for time.)
\par 
\par The }{\f2 <classification name>}{ is a coded value that specifies the formulae used by the math transform.  See }{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst { HYPERLINK  \\l "_Parameterized_Transforms" }{{\*\datafield 
08d0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b02000000080000001a0000005f0050006100720061006d00650074006500720069007a00650064005f005400720061006e00730066006f0072006d007300000000}}}{\fldrslt {\cs26\ul\cf2 Parameterized Transforms}}}{
 for legal values, and the corresponding parameters.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925578}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.13\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {PASSTHROUGH_MT{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925578}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {This is a m
ath transform that passes through a subset of ordinates to another transform. This allows transforms to operate on a subset of ordinates. For example, if you have (Lat,Lon,Height) coordinates, then you may wish to convert the height values from meters to 
feet without affecting the (Lat,Lon) values. If you wanted to affect the (Lat,Lon) values and leave the Height values alone, then you would have to swap the ordinates around to (Height,Lat,Lon). You can do this with an affine map.
\par 
\par The }{\f2 <integer>}{ argument is the index of the first affected ordinate.  The }{\f2 <math transform> }{argument is the transform to pass coordinates onto.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925579}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.14\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {PRIMEM{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925579}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {This defines the meridian used to take longitude measurements from. The units of the }{\f2 <longitude>}{ m
ust be inferred from the context.  If the PRIMEM clause occurs inside a GEOGCS, then the longitude units will match those of the geographic coordinate system.  If the PRIMEM clause occurs inside a GEOCCS, then the units will be in degrees.
\par 
\par The longitude value defines the angle of the prime meridian relative to the Greenwich Meridian.  A positive value indicates the prime meridian is East of Greenwich, and a negative value indicates the prime meridian is West of Greenwich.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925580}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.15\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {PROJCS{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925580}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
This indicates a projected coordinate system.  The PROJECTION sub-clause contains the classification name used by the CT_MathTransformFactory::CreateParameterizedTransform method, and the PARAMETER clauses specify the parameters.  However, th
e units used by CT_MathTransformFactory are always meters and degrees, and the units in the PARAMETER clauses are in the linear/angular units of the PROJCS/GEOGCS respectively.  So if you are writing code to read or write WKT, then you must use the IsPara
meterAngular and IsParameterLinear methods to do the unit conversions - be careful!
\par 
\par (Notice that this handling of units is slightly different from the way the EPSG 4 database works.  In the EPSG 4 database, each transformation parameter value defines its o
wn units. However, 99% of the EPSG projection parameter units are the same as the units of the corresponding projected coordinate system.)
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925581}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.16\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {PROJECTION{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925581}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {This describes a projection from geographic coordinates to projected coo
rdinates.  It is used inside a PROJCS to define the parameters of the projection transform.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925582}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.17\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {SPHEROID{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925582}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
This describes a spheroid, which is an approximation of the Earth's surface as a squashed sphere. In this document, the terms \'93spheroid\'94 and \'93ellipsoid\'94 are synonymous. The term  \'93SPHEROID\'94
 is used in WKT for compatibility with Simple Features.  However, the term \'93ellipsoid\'94 is preferred elsewhere in this specification.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925583}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.18\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {TOWGS84{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925583}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {This indicate
s a list of up to 7 Bursa Wolf transformation parameters.  These parameters can be used to approximate a transformation from the horizontal datum to the WGS84 datum.  However, it must be remembered that this transformation is only an approximation.  For a
 given horizontal datum, different Bursa Wolf transformations can be used to minimize the errors over different regions.
\par 
\par If the DATUM clause contains a TOWGS84 clause, then this should be its \'93preferred\'94 transformation, which will often be the transformati
on which gives a broad approximation over the whole area of interest (e.g. the area of interest in the containing geographic coordinate system).
\par 
\par Sometimes, only the first three or six parameters are defined.  In this case the remaining parameters must be 
zero.  If only three parameters are defined, then they can still be plugged into the Bursa Wolf formulas, or you can take a short cut.  The Bursa Wolf transformation works on geocentric coordinates, so you cannot apply it onto geographic coordinates direc
tly.  If there are only three parameters then you can use the Molodenski or abridged Molodenski formulas.
\par 
\par The DATUM clause may not contain a TOWGS84 clause in the following situations:
\par 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 a)\tab}}\pard \ql \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls38\pnrnot0\pnlcltr\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnsp120\pnhang{\pntxta )}}
\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls38\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {The writing application was using the Simple Features specification, which does not specify TOWGS84 as a valid keyword
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 b)\tab}}\pard \ql \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls38\pnrnot0\pnlcltr\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnsp120\pnhang{\pntxta )}}
\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls38\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {The writing application did not have an available transformation.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 c)\tab}}\pard \ql \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls38\pnrnot0\pnlcltr\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnsp120\pnhang{\pntxta )}}
\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls38\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {There is no possible transformation.  For example, the horizontal datum could be a surface that rotates relative to the Earth\rquote s surface.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
\par In particular, if the DATUM does contain a TOWGS84 clause, and the parameter values are zero, then the receiving application can assume that the writing application believed that the datum is approximately equal to WGS84.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925584}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.19\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {UNIT{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925584}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
This describes units used for values elsewhere within the parent WKT clause (sometimes including descendants of the parent clause).
\par 
\par The physical dimension (i.e. type) of the units is determined by context.  For example, in a GEOGCS the type of the units is angular.  In a VERT_CS the type of the units is linear.
\par 
\par Within a UNIT clause, the units are described by relating them to a fundam
ental unit of that type with a conversion factor.  For linear units, the conversion factor is the scalar value that converts the described units into meters.  For angular units, the conversion factor is the scalar value that converts the described units i
nto radians.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925585}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.20\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {VERT_DATUM{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925585}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {This indicates the vertical datum, or method used for vertical measurements.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925586}{\listtext\pard\plain\s3 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.3.21\tab}}\pard\plain \s3\ql \fi-1008\li1008\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx1008\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl2\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin1008\itap0 \b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {VERT_CS{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925586}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {This indicates a vertical coordinate system.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _WKT_Example}{\*\bkmkend _WKT_Example}{\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7.4\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\ql \fi-864\li864\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
