\par {\*\bkmkend _Toc365351276}{\*\bkmkend _Toc467222158}{\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \b\fs28 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 8\tab}}\pard\plain \s1\ql \fi-720\li720\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar
\jclisttab\tx720\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 \b\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\page {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925588}Relationship to Simple Features{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925588}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par \'93Simple Features\'94 is an earlier interface specification adopted by OGC.  The Simple Features specification includes two packages: Geometry and Spatial Reference Systems (SRS).
\par 
\par The CS package in this specification covers the same ground as the Simple Features SRS package.  The SRS package was based on a subset of the coordinate systems in the EPSG abs
tract model.  The CS package extends this abstract model to encompass all EPSG coordinate systems, including vertical coordinate systems and compound coordinate systems. CS then goes further to handle more than 3 dimensions and ungeoreferenced coordinate 
systems.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925589}{\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 8.1\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\ql \fi-864\li864\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx864\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin864\itap0 
\b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Compatibility of Well-Known Text{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925589}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {The CS package keeps the WKT serializing concept of Simple Features SRS. In fact, }{\b 
all Simple Features SRS Well-Known Text strings are valid in CS, and have exactly the same meaning}{.  This ensures that all stored Simple Features SRS data will be compatible with the new CS package.
\par 
\par The Geographic Transform interface in the Simple Features SRS package has been absorbed into the CT package as a range of different math transforms (e.g. Molo
denski).  This does not affect WKT compatibility, since the WKT for geographic transformations was never defined.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925590}{\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 8.2\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\ql \fi-864\li864\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx864\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin864\itap0 
\b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Name changes from SF-SRS to CS{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925590}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {The CS package basically just renames all the Simple Features SRS interfaces by adding the \'93CS_\'94
 prefix, and then removes all the mutating methods.  The functionality of the mutating methods (e.g. changing the longitude of a Prime Meridian) has been moved into the enlarged factory interfaces.  A couple of the old Simple Features inter
faces have been moved into other packages (see below).
\par 
\par Since most of the method names have been left unchanged from Simple Fe
atures, it is possible for objects to support both sets of interfaces.  For example, a geographic coordinate system object (e.g. MyGCS) can easily support both CS_GeographicCoordinateSystem (from CS) and IGeographicCoordinateSystem (from SF).  This means 
that the object MyGCS can be used with code that expects Simple Features interfaces or code that expects CS interfaces.
\par 
\par One notable name change is the method to get an entity\rquote s well-known text.  For example, in COM Simple Features this property was \'93WellKnownText\'94, whereas in CS the property is called \'93WKT\'94
.  This is done deliberately, so a new object which supports both SF and CS interfaces can tell whether it is being asked for an SF compatible WKT string, or a CS compatible WKT string.  If it is asked fo
r an SF compatible string then it should not include the new optional clauses.  If the object is not part of the SF abstract model (e.g. a 3D coordinate system) then it should either not support the SF interfaces, or it should fail the WellKnownText metho
d.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925591}{\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 8.3\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\ql \fi-864\li864\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx864\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin864\itap0 
\b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Authority Codes{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925591}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
The CS and CT packages use a String for the Authority Code, whereas Simple Features used an Integer.  This change was made for compatibility with those authorities that use String codes.
\par 
\par As a result, the Simple Features ISpatialReferenceInfo \'93Code\'94 property will fail if the CS_Info \'93AuthorityCode\'94 property cannot be represented as an integer.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s1 \b\fs28 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 9\tab}}\pard\plain \s1\ql \fi-720\li720\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx720\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 
\b\fs28\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\page {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925592}Processes{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925592}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\par Common processes are shown here as scenarios.  Some scenarios refer to previous scenarios, so you may find it convenient to read them in order.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925593}{\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 9.1\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\ql \fi-864\li864\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx864\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin864\itap0 
\b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Create a NAD27 California Zone 1 CS{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925593}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
In this example, a client wishes to get a coordinate system for California zone 1, based on the NAD27 geoid.  The units of the coordinate system will be in feet.
\par 
\par The client does not know (or care) what projection this CS uses, let alone the correct parameter values to use for that projection.  However, they do know the EPSG code, which is 26741.
\par 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1)\tab}}\pard \ql \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls33\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnsp120\pnhang{\pntxta )}}
\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls33\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {Create a CS_CoordinateSystemAuthorityFactory
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
\par EPSG is a coordinate system \'93authority\'94, so firstly the client needs to create a CS_CoordinateSystemAuthorityFactory.
\par 
\par In the COM DCP they could write a loop to iterate through all the available CS_CoordinateSystemAuthorityFactory implementations, testing each one to see if its authority name was \'93EPSG\'94.
\par 
\par In other DCPs, or if they knew the class name of the EPSG authority factory object within their implementation, they could dynamically create the object by name.
\par 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2)\tab}}\pard \ql \fi-360\li360\ri0\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\ilvl0\ls33\pnrnot0\pndec\pnstart1\pnindent360\pnsp120\pnhang{\pntxta )}}
\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls33\adjustright\rin0\lin360\itap0 {Use authority factory to create CS
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
\par In pseudo-code:
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof Dim csaf as  CS_CoordinateSystemAuthorityFactory
\par csaf = GetMyEpsgFactory()
\par dim cs as CS_CoordinateSystem
\par cs = csaf.CreateHorizontalCoordinateSystem(26741)
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925594}{\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 9.2\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\ql \fi-864\li864\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx864\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin864\itap0 
\b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Create a NAD83 California Zone 1 CS{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925594}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
This process is identical to the process above, except that the EPSG code for a NAD83 projection is 26941.  Also, the EPSG NAD83 coordinate system uses meters instead of feet.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925595}{\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 9.3\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\ql \fi-864\li864\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx864\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin864\itap0 
\b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Store and recall CS in a Database{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925595}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {T
he client may have lots of point data that uses coordinates in NAD27 California Zone 1.  They can easily store the points in a two-column table, but how can they store the coordinate system and retrieve it later?
\par 
\par One solution would be to store the EPSG code of the CS (26741).  But if they do this, then other software which does not know about EPSG, or which will not have an EPSG factory, will not be able to georeference the points correctly.
\par 
\par An alternative would be to store the CS in Well-Known Text format.  (This is what the SQL92 schema of the Simple Feature specification does.)
\par 
\par To do this, the client would get the WKT property from the CS object.  The WKT property is a text string, so it is easy to store in a database.
\par 
\par Later, other software could read the WKT string and create their own CS object by using a CS_CoordinateSystemFactory as follows:
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof Dim csf as CS_CoordinateSystemFactory
\par csf = GetMyCoordsysFactory()
\par Dim wkt as String
\par wkt = ReadWellKnownTextFromDB()
\par dim cs as CS_CoordinateSystem
\par cs = csf.CreateFromWKT(wkt)
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
\par Please notice that the above example uses a normal factory, and not an \'93authority\'94 factory.
\par 
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925596}{\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 9.4\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\ql \fi-864\li864\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx864\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin864\itap0 
\b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Merge California Zone 1 data in NAD27 and NAD83{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925596} 
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {If a cl
ient has an old table of California zone 1 points in NAD27 feet, and a new table of California zone 1 points in NAD83 meters, then they may want to merge the old table into the new table.  To do this they will need to perform a coordinate transformation.

\par 
\par Firstly, the client can get WKT strings for the two coordinate systems.  (If the WKT strings for the coordinate systems are stored with the point data, then they can skip this step.)
\par 
\par Secondly, the client can get a CT_CoordinateTransformation between the two coordinate systems.  This will get details of the required transformation, but will not actually do any transforming operations.
\par 
\par Thirdly, the client can retrieve the CT_MathTransform from the CT_CoordinateTransformation.
\par 
\par Finally, the client can use the CT_MathTransform to transform the old point data into the NAD83 coordinate system, and then add the transformed points to the new table.
\par 
\par In pseudo code:
\par 
\par }\pard \ql \li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof Rem Firstly get WKT of tables
\par Dim wktOld as String
\par Dim wktNew as String
\par wktOld = GetOldTableCS()
\par wktNew = GetNewTableCS()
\par 
\par Rem Secondly get a transformation
\par Dim ctf as new CT_CoordinateTransformationFactory
\par Dim ct as CT_CoordinateTransformation
\par ct = ctf.CreateFromCoordinateSystems( wktOld, wktNew )
\par 
\par Rem Thirdly retrieve the math transform
\par Dim mt as CT_MathTransform
\par mt = ct.MathTransform
\par 
\par Rem Finally transform and merge the old points
\par While (OldPointAvailable())
\par     Dim ptOld as PT_CoordinatePoint
\par     ptOld.Ord.resize(2)
\par     ptOld.Ord[0] = ReadPointX()
\par     ptOld.Ord[1] = ReadPointY()
\par     Dim ptNew as PT_CoordinatePoint
\par     ptNew = mt.Transform( ptOld )
\par     StoreNewPoint (ptNew.Ord[0], ptNew.Ord[1] )
\par End while
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {
\par {\*\bkmkstart _Toc496925597}{\listtext\pard\plain\s2 \b \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 9.5\tab}}\pard\plain \s2\ql \fi-864\li864\ri0\sb120\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx864\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls3\ilvl1\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin864\itap0 
\b\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Transform steps from NAD27 to NAD83 in California Zone 1{\*\bkmkend _Toc496925597}
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {The math transform used in the previous scenario contains many steps.
\par 
\par It is the job of the CT_CoordinateTransformationFactory to analyze the source and target coordinate systems to find a series of transform steps that will make up the complete transformation.
\par 
\par Here is a possible math transform for the previous scenario in Well-Known Text format:  (Embedded comments are shown in bold.  These comments are not valid in WKT format, and are only included here to explain what the steps are doing.)
\par 
\par }{\b\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof // Use concatenated transform
\par }{\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof CONCAT_MT[
\par     }{\b\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof // Use affine map to convert feet into meters.
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     PARAM_MT["Affine",
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof         PARAMETER["num_row",3],
\par         PARAMETER["num_col",3],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_0_0",0.3048006096012192],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_0_1",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_0_2",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_1_0",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_1_1",0.3048006096012192],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_1_2",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_2_0",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_2_1",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_2_2",1]
\par     ],
\par }{\b\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     // Undo the California state plane projection.
\par }{\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     INVERSE_MT[
\par }{\b\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof         // Projection converts metres to (lon,lat).
\par }{\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof         PARAM_MT["Lambert_Conformal_Conic_2SP",
\par             PARAMETER["latitude_of_origin",41.66666666666662],
\par             PARAMETER["central_meridian",39.99999999999996],
\par             PARAMETER["standard_parallel_1",39.3333333333333],
\par             PARAMETER["standard_parallel_2",-121.9999999999999],
\par             PARAMETER["false_easting",609601.2192024385],
\par             PARAMETER["false_northing",0],
\par             PARAMETER["semi_major",6378206.4],
\par             PARAMETER["semi_minor",6356583.8]
\par         ]
\par     ],
\par }{\b\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     // Use affine map to change (lon,lat) to (lon,lat,0).
\par }{\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     PARAM_MT["Affine",
\par         PARAMETER["num_row",4],
\par         PARAMETER["num_col",3],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_0_0",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_0_1",1],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_0_2",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_1_0",1],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_1_1",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_1_2",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_2_0",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_2_1",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_2_2",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_3_0",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_3_1",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_3_2",1]
\par     ],
\par }{\b\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     // Convert (lon,lat,0) to geocentric (X,Y,Z).
\par }{\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     PARAM_MT["Ellipsoid_To_Geocentric",
\par         PARAMETER["semi_major",6378206.4],
\par         PARAMETER["semi_minor",6356583.8]
\par     ],
\par }{\b\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     // Use affine map for Bursa Wolf transformation.
\par }{\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     PARAM_MT["Affine",
\par         PARAMETER["num_row",4],
\par         PARAMETER["num_col",4],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_0_0",1],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_0_1",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_0_2",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_0_3",3],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_1_0",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_1_1",1],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_1_2",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_1_3",-142],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_2_0",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_2_1",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_2_2",1],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_2_3",-183],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_3_0",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_3_1",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_3_2",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_3_3",1]
\par     ],
\par }{\b\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     // Convert (X,Y,Z) to (lon,lat,hgt).
\par }{\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     PARAM_MT["Geocentric_To_Ellipsoid",
\par         PARAMETER["semi_major",6378137],
\par         PARAMETER["semi_minor",6356752.314140356]
\par     ],
\par }{\b\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     // Discard height, converting (lon,lat,hgt) into (lon,lat).
\par }{\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     PARAM_MT["Affine",
\par         PARAMETER["num_row",3],
\par         PARAMETER["num_col",4],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_0_0",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_0_1",1],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_0_2",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_0_3",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_1_0",1],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_1_1",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_1_2",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_1_3",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_2_0",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_2_1",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_2_2",0],
\par         PARAMETER["elt_2_3",1]
\par     ],
\par }{\b\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     // Reapply state plane projection.
\par }{\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof     PARAM_MT["Lambert_Conformal_Conic_2SP",
\par         PARAMETER["latitude_of_origin",41.66666666666662],
\par         PARAMETER["central_meridian",39.99999999999996],
\par         PARAMETER["standard_parallel_1",39.3333333333333],
\par         PARAMETER["standard_parallel_2",-121.9999999999999],
\par         PARAMETER["false_easting",2000000],
\par         PARAMETER["false_northing",500000],
\par         PARAMETER["semi_major",6378137],
\par         PARAMETER["semi_minor",6356752.314140356]
\par     ]
\par }\pard\plain \s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f2\lang1024\langfe1024\noproof ]
