\par 
\par }{This transform operates on 3D coordinates.  The first input ordinate is the longitude in degrees, and the second input ordinate is the latitude in degrees.  The third input ordinate is the height above the ellipsoid in meters.
\par  
\par (These formulas and equations are copied from the EPSG 4.3 database.)
\par 
\par Latitude, P, and Longitude, L, in terms of Geographic Coordinate System (GCS) A may 
\par be expressed in terms of a geocentric (earth centered) Cartesian coordinate system X, Y, Z 
\par with the Z axis corresponding with the Polar axis positive northwards, the X axis through 
\par the intersection of the Greenwich meridian and equator, and the Y axis through the 
\par intersection of the equator with longitude 90 degrees E. If the GCS's prime meridian is not 
\par Greenwich, longitudes must first be converted to their Greenwich equivalent. If the earth's 
\par spheroidal semi major axis is a, semi minor axis  b, and inverse flattening 1/f,  then
\par 
\par    }{\lang1036\langfe1033\langnp1036 XA=   (nu + hA) cos P cos L
\par    YA=   (nu + hA) cos P sin L
\par    ZA=  ((1 - e^2) nu + hA) sin P
\par 
\par }{where nu is the prime vertical radius of curvature at latitude P and is equal to 
\par    nu = a /(1 - e^2*sin^2(P))^0.5,
\par    P and L are respectively the latitude and longitude (related to Greenwich) of the 
\par point 
\par    h is height above the ellipsoid, (topographic height plus geoidal height), and
\par    e is the eccentricity of the ellipsoid where e^2 = (a^2 -b^2)/a^2 = 2f -f^2
\par 
