\par }{ (These formulas and equations are copied from the EPSG 4.3 database.)
\par 
\par Cartesian coordinates in geocentric coordinate system  B may be used 
\par to derive geographical coordinates in terms of geographic coordinate system B by:
\par    P   =  arctan (ZB + e^2* nu*sin P) / (XB^2 + YB^2)^0.5 by iteration
\par    L   = arctan YB/XB
\par    }{\lang1036\langfe1033\langnp1036 hB  =  XB sec L sec P  - nu
\par 
\par }{where LB is relative to Greenwich. If the geographic system has a non Greenwich prime 
\par meridian, the Greenwich value of the local prime meridian should be applied to longitude.
\par 
\par (Note that h is the height above the ellipsoid. This is the height value which is 
\par delivered by Transit and GPS satellite observations but is not the topographic 
\par height value which is normally used for national mapping and leveling operations. 
\par The topographic height is usually the height above mean sea level or an alternative 
\par level reference for the country. If one starts with a topographic height,  it will be 
\par necessary to convert it to an ellipsoid height before using the above transformation 
\par formulas. h = N + H, where N is the geoid height above the ellipsoid at the point 
\par and is sometimes negative, and H is the height of the point above the geoid. The 
\par height above the geoid is often taken to be that above mean sea level, perhaps with 
\par a constant correction applied. Geoid heights of points above the nationally used 
\par ellipsoid may not be readily available. For the WGS84 ellipsoid the value of N, 
\par representing the height of the geoid relative to the ellipsoid, can vary between 
\par values of -100m in the Sri Lanka area to +60m in the North Atlantic.)
\par 
