\par This transform can operate on 2D or 3D coordinates.  In either case the first ordinate is the longitude in degrees, and the second ordinate is the latitude in degrees.  In the 3D form the third ordinate is the height above the ellipsoid in meters.
\par 
\par As an a
lternative to the computation of the new latitude, longitude and height above ellipsoid in discrete steps through geocentric coordinates, the changes in these coordinates may be derived directly by formulas derived by Molodenski. Abridged versions of thes
e formulas, which are quite satisfactory for three parameter transformations, are as follows:
\par 
\par (These formulas and equations are copied from the EPSG 4.3 database.)
\par 
\par Dlat " = [(-dX*sin(lat)*cos(lon)) - (dY*sin(lat)*sin(lon)) + (dZ*cos(lat)) + (((a*Df) + (f*Da))*sin(2*lat))] / (rho * sin(1"))
\par 
\par }{\lang1036\langfe1033\langnp1036 Dlon " = (-dX*sin(lon) + dY*cos(lon)) / ((nu*cos(lat)) * sin(1"))
\par 
\par Dh = (dX*cos(lat)*cos(lon)) + (dY*cos(lat)*sin(lon)) + (dZ*sin(lat)) + ((a*Df + f*Da)*(sin(lat)^2)) - Da
\par 
\par }{where the dX, dY and dZ terms are as before, a
nd rho and nu are the meridian and prime vertical radii of curvature at the given latitude (lat) on the first ellipsoid (see section on Geographic/Geocentric formulas), Da is the difference in the semi-major axes (a1 - a2) of the first and second ellipsoi
ds and Df  is the difference in the flattening of the two ellipsoids.
\par 
\par The formulas for Dlat and Dlon indicate changes in latitude and longitude in arc-seconds.
